abstract: PHILADELPHIA, June 5. -- Since the edict of the New-York Stock Exchange committee abolishing arbitraging, the local operators have been looking around for other stocks to trade in. abstract: NEW-LONDON, Conn., June 9 -- The Pequot House opened for the season Tuesday. abstract: CHICAGO, June 9. -- The stock market was quite active for a Saturday. There were transactions in everything on the list, but, excepting in two stocks, there were no radical changes in prices. West Chicago was weak and Diamond Match strong. The former opened 3/8 below the closing figures of yesterday, at 142 3/8, and dropped down to 141 1/2.

abstract: The Harlem Wheelmen are beginning to make arrangements for what they confidently prophesy will be one of the biggest race meets New-York has ever seen, to be held on Sept. 15, at Manhattan Field. They have already raised $1,000 toward defraying expenses, and the Board of Managers in whose hands the development of the whole affair is placed mean to turn every week of the long gap between now and September to the best advantage.

abstract: BERLIN, June 9 -- M. Hanotaux, France's Minister of Foreign Affairs, touched a responsive chord in Germany when he attacked England's policy in Africa before the Chamber of Deputies last Thursday. abstract: The critical temperature of oxygen is -171, ( -113 C.) Above that point it remains obstinately gaseous -- interstitial movements are too active to permit its molecules to lay hold one of another. Such cold is unattainable by direct means; the intervention of liquid oxygen is required to produce it.

abstract: -- Thomas Ellis, for many years prominent in this city as a jobber in grain and flour, died in Cincinnati Friday. He was burn near that city in 1813 and began business as a trader along the Ohio River. In 1853 be came to New-York and for twenty-five years did a large business in grain and flour. For twenty years he was an operator at the Produce Exchange.

abstract: AUGUSTA, Kan., June 11. -- The Walnut River is out of its banks and enormous damage has been done to crops. Wheat in the shock was swept down the stream, and that not harvested has been ruined. Fences and buildings have been washed away, and for more than a mile the St. Louis and San Francisco track is under water, and the transfer bridgre has been taken out six miles north, stopping traffic.

abstract: ROCKVILLE, Conn., June 16. -- Frederick J. Titus of the Riverside Wheelmen to-day rode the fastest trial mile of the year at the race meet of the Rockville Wheel Club. The day was fine and the track unusually good. Last season Zimmerman could not beat 2:21 on its surface, owing to the dust. Titus rode against the State record of 2:15 made by "Willie" Windle on this track, doing 2:07 easily.

abstract: GLASGOW, June 18. -- The Vigilant was towed to Glasgow from Gourock this morning and docked at the Hendersons shipyard. Capt. Haff has joined the yacht, and she will be fitted out at once under a covered shed. abstract: W.S. Hobart of San Francisco is going into coaching and will have a six-in-hand on the roads about here shortly. abstract: CHICAGO, June 19 -- The boom was out of wheat to-day, and prices were almost as weak as they were strong yesterday. They did not break as quickly nor with such nervous excitement as they displayed when advancing, but melted away gradually under the pressure of long wheat that did not all come out at once. Yesterday's enthusiastic buyers were cautious sellers to-day, and the seaboard let go of immense quantities throughout the session.

abstract: In Worth's shops in Paris, says a London print, there is dignity and severity almost classical. Everything is strict, correct, comma il faut. abstract: NEW-LONDON, Conn., June 23 -- Notwithstanding the terrific heat to-day the crews on the river did as hard work this evening as at any time during their stay here. The temperature to-day was as high as it will probably go during the Summer, the thermometer showing 91 at the signal office. The noon practice was light because of the heat and to husband the strength of the crews for the severer trials this evening.

abstract: The musical value of a Saengerfest is not to be measured by the artistic merits of its concerts. This seeming paradox may be readily explained. At a Saengerfest hundreds of singing societies from various parts of the country assemble, and they inevitably sing together. It is generally conceded that a chorus of 100 can Sing better than one of 1,000, although it cannot make so much noise.

abstract: -- A small-sized strike occurred on the Grammar School Building at Eighty-first Street and Avenue A yesterday. For several days the cornice and skylight workmen have been engaged in putting in ventilators. The tin and sheetiron workmen contended that this work came under their supervision. The walking delegate of the latter union visited the building and induced six of the twelve men at work to Quit.

abstract: CHICAGO, June 29 -- The close on wheat to-day was 1/8c higher than yesterday, but the tone throughout the entire session and until within a few minute the end of the day's trading was decidedly weak, and prices ruled 1/4 @ 3/4c under Thursday's final figures. The rally came about through the sale of 17,000 bushels of cash wheat by Seaverns, who afterward posed in the market as a buyer of the futures.
